pr_review_comment_body:
`azure.common.AzureHttpError: The specifed resource name contains invalid characters.`
That cause of error. The line called `azure.storage.blob.baseblobservice.BaseBlobService.exists()`, Then the function check exists **The CONTAINER NAME**, not FULL PATH. So It need to fix. 

On `backends.dropbox`, exists function such as 
```python
    def exists(self, name):
        try:
            return bool(self.client.metadata(self._full_path(name)))
        except ErrorResponse:
            return False
```

Checking the way `getNewReloadTriggerParams()` is used, I think including null values is fine, so this could be simplified to:

```js
return Object.assign(
  {},
  ...ThResultSetStore.reloadOnChangeParameters.map(prop => ({
    [prop]: locationSearch[prop]
  }))
);
```

I'm afraid I don't follow. This is `Headers.__init__()`:

```python
    def __init__(self, rawHeaders=None):
        self._rawHeaders = {}
        if rawHeaders is not None:
            for name, values in rawHeaders.items():
                self.setRawHeaders(name, values)
```

It calls `setRawHeaders()` which is [clearly documented](https://twistedmatrix.com/documents/17.1.0/api/twisted.web.http_headers.Headers.html#setRawHeaders) as accepting `bytes` or `unicode`. This enhancement was done as part of the Python 3 porting work, if I recall correctly, and it has prompted the removal of lots of not-quite-right header encoding code from `treq`. Like, in particular, the stuff that assumed headers were ASCII that prompted this PR in the first place. :-)

In any case I actually _am_ passing `bytes` here. I just wrote out the literals as `u''` because it makes the test easier to read than the equivalent backslash escapes. Plus, it keeps the lines shorter.

If you're asking, "why would a Content-Type header contain Unicode in real life", well, I hope that doesn't actually happen, but I don't see any reason that treq should produce a UnicodeDecodeError should such a thing happen. In particular, it shouldn't do that _on Python 3 but not on Python 2_.

